  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 7:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This interruption, no notice of which, seemingly (but see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 7:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is taken by Jesus in His subsequent words, is a characteristic indication of the genuineness of the narrative.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁ ὄχλος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the multitude",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (not the same as the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἰουδαίοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 7:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), unprejudiced, and unacquainted with the designs of the hierarchy, at least so far as they referred to the death of Christ, consisting for the most part, probably, of pilgrims to the feast.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δαιμόνιον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] causing in you such perverted and wicked suspicions. Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 8:48",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 10:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". An expression not of ill-will (Hengstenberg and early writers), but of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "amazement",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that a man who taught so admirably should imagine what they deem to be a moral impossibility and a dark delusion. It must, they thought, be a fixed idea put into his mind by some daemon, a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κακοδαιμονᾶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 7:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This, some of the crowd think mere raving. He is a monomaniac labouring under a hallucination that people wish to kill Him.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Δαιμόνιον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " … ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀποκτεῖναι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; This question, repudiating the idea that any one seeks to slay Him, needs no answer and gets none.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thou hast a devil",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The multitude who have come up from the provinces know nothing of the designs of the hierarchy, although dwellers in Jerusalem (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "John 7:25",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 7:25",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") are better informed. These provincials think He must be possessed to have such an idea. Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 10:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 11:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the same is quoted as said of the Baptist. In both cases extraordinary conduct is supposed to be evidence of insanity, and the insanity is attributed to demoniacal possession. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 8:48",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the same remark is made, but in a much more hostile spirit (see note there); and there Christ answers the charge. Here, where it is the mere ignorant rejoinder of a perplexed multitude, He takes no notice of the interruption.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 7:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Καὶ εἶπε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and said",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") At Jerusalem there seem to have been some lying in wait to kill Him, and others to have known the fact; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 7:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “Then said some of them of Jerusalem, Is not this He, whom they seek to kill?” and those who speak here seem to have been farther removed from these, and yet not at heart better. Jesus shows that He has a deeper knowledge of them, and He penetrates them with this ray [of His omniscience].—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δαιμόνιον ἔχεις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "thou hast a demon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") The foulest formula of reviling. Possessed, mad. They think, that the hidden design to murder Him could not have become known to Jesus Himself except through an evil spirit.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 20-24.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(3)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Treatment of the ignorance and insolence of the multitude.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 20.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The multitude,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " who broke out in angry and ignorant remonstrance, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "answered",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (and said). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Thou hast a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "daemon. Who is seeking to kill thee?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Thou must have some evil spirit tormenting thee with such cruel and melancholy foreboding (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 8:48",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 10:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This was an outburst of insolent and ignorant amazement on their part, that One who taught so wonderfully \"should imagine what they deem a moral impossibility and dark delusion\" (Meyer). The design rankling in the hearts of the authorities was too well known to our Lord, and, not deigning to notice the interruption and the insult, he continued - John 7:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
